  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3817540603" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3817540603" />
    <a title="M.J." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/146594-m-j"><img alt="M.J." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363351707p2/146594.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3817540603?book_show_action=true">Feb 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M.J." class="user" itemprop="url" name="M.J." href="/user/show/146594-m-j">M.J.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780345356574" href="/book/show/979508.A_Man_Rides_Through">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/146594-m-j?shelf=nostalgia">nostalgia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/146594-m-j?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3817540603" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6259640839239568349">Stephen R. Donaldson’s “A Man Rides Through” is the concluding novel in his two-book series and improves on its predecessor, addressing many of its flaws, but still feels lacking. <br/><br/>(This review is part of my “Nostalgia” series, where I infrequently revisit a small collection of fantasy novels in my possession—most of which I inherited rather than collected—to determine if they hold up decades later and are worth keeping.)<br/><br/>Transplanted from our own world into a fantasy world where all mirrors are m</span>
  <span id="freeText6259640839239568349" style="display:none">Stephen R. Donaldson’s “A Man Rides Through” is the concluding novel in his two-book series and improves on its predecessor, addressing many of its flaws, but still feels lacking. <br /><br />(This review is part of my “Nostalgia” series, where I infrequently revisit a small collection of fantasy novels in my possession—most of which I inherited rather than collected—to determine if they hold up decades later and are worth keeping.)<br /><br />Transplanted from our own world into a fantasy world where all mirrors are magic mirrors, young (a)socialite Terisa Morgan is drawn deeper into the events that pose an existential threat to the kingdom of Mordant and its neighbours, discovering her own abilities and strength as she squares off against the evil men seeking to (of course) rule the world.<br /><br />In my review of the previous novel, I stated that in the face of myriad frustrations with the story I was driven more by curiosity as to whether Donaldson would stick the landing with his conclusion than anything else. The answer is... sort of. He addresses many of the flaws of the first book—the main protagonist largely gives up her passivity, the book shifts to alternative points of view after a tight third person perspective that just did not serve the previous book well, and moves from shadowy threats to actual events—that makes this concluding book a more satisfying read, but feeling unearned at times.<br /><br />Where it feels the weakest is in its characters. It boasts a wide cast of characters, each distinct from one another, but many of them little more than a single theme. The cartoonish main antagonist, in particular, detracts from the reader truly investing in the narrative, as he gets more mileage from the threat of sexual violence (this threat is far too often deployed) than any real sense of menace about his ability to cause havoc on an international scale. Terisa, the main protagonist, is mercifully more interesting in this book, though the transformation does seem a bit quick given how long we languished with her as an inaction heroine in the previous novel.<br /><br />Ultimately, the writing and new direction are good enough to propel the narrative along and convince the reader to avoid thinking too deeply about the plot (or how many things manage to fall “just so” to give it the outcome it has), but not enough to elevate it far beyond its shortcomings. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6259640839239568349" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

