<div id="review_844966062" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/844966062" />
    <a title="Kaila" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5819724-kaila"><img alt="Kaila" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1395784773p2/5819724.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/844966062?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kaila" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kaila" href="/user/show/5819724-kaila">Kaila</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer844966062" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11603369843738548088">In some ways A Man Rides Through is an improvement on the previous book; in other ways it is worse. All in all, I think I enjoyed it less than the previous book, despite the fact that the biggest flaw (Terisa) is no longer as huge of an issue as she was - plus we get a few over POVs sprinkled through.<br/><br/>One of my largest gripes is that the author hasn&apos;t lost his habit of over-explaining, and often to the deteriment of the reader&apos;s actual understanding. In fact, some of these conversations where thi</span>
  <span id="freeText11603369843738548088" style="display:none">In some ways A Man Rides Through is an improvement on the previous book; in other ways it is worse. All in all, I think I enjoyed it less than the previous book, despite the fact that the biggest flaw (Terisa) is no longer as huge of an issue as she was - plus we get a few over POVs sprinkled through.<br /><br />One of my largest gripes is that the author hasn't lost his habit of over-explaining, and often to the deteriment of the reader's actual understanding. In fact, some of these conversations where things are revealed or repeated feel like non-sequitur, as a character will say something and we have no idea why they've said it because it either a) has little relation to what was asked but is apparently the answer, or b) is a sudden change in direction.<br /><br />Repetition is still the name of the game.<br /><br />There is also quite a lot of rape/pre-rape in the book and it honestly feels overdone, as if the author can't imagine anything worse actually happening to these characters (and not just women, either). It sounds awful but it gets boring, which is probably not what was intentioned at all and definitely shouldn't happen, but does carry on from where the previous book left off, so isn't all that shocking. It therefore comes across as far less serious than it is - especially when certain actions are just brushed off.<br /><br />If I'm honest the fact that, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Terisa even considered going home and needed 'to hear the horns' to decide to stay  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> irritated me. In my mind, there was absolutely no doubt about what was going to happen next. <br /><br />Things are a little far-fetched too.<br /><br />If this review sounds like it isn't for a three star book this is because the good points are less clear. Oh, the book is well-structured and well enough written, the pacing is fine, romances are well-established and there are characters and scenes to like, but they don't really explain what I like. I suppose some of the more cheesy moments that are typical in a fantasy novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11603369843738548088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


