<div id="review_3035840465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3035840465" />
    <a title="Andy Mangham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51012819-andy-mangham"><img alt="Andy Mangham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451859491p2/51012819.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3035840465?book_show_action=true">Nov 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andy Mangham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andy Mangham" href="/user/show/51012819-andy-mangham">Andy Mangham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3035840465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15411342670780990098">A Man Rides Through improved a few of the big problems of the first book, particularly in the character-development arena. Terisa claims much more agency over the course of the novel, and it was refreshing and fun to watch her navigate the world with Geridan, who also comes more out of his shell. I can&apos;t deny that the two of them have a great chemistry that pushes the book forward, and I enjoyed watching their relationship deepen.<br/>I was also more than a little disappointed with A Man Rides Throug</span>
  <span id="freeText15411342670780990098" style="display:none">A Man Rides Through improved a few of the big problems of the first book, particularly in the character-development arena. Terisa claims much more agency over the course of the novel, and it was refreshing and fun to watch her navigate the world with Geridan, who also comes more out of his shell. I can't deny that the two of them have a great chemistry that pushes the book forward, and I enjoyed watching their relationship deepen.<br />I was also more than a little disappointed with A Man Rides Through. While the book improves upon its character work, the narrative itself takes a serious nose dive. I don't believe I'm one to get overly upset over plot, but as the story progressed, the amount of plot-holes, unrealistic/incredible (in the bad way) complications, and out-of-character decisions became completely unbearable. I'm sorry to say it, because I really wanted to like this book, but there were a few moments during my read where I literally threw up my hands and cried "Why!?", as completely preventable disasters seemed to arise just because Donaldson wanted them to. The book just lost credibility with me after a certain point. It no longer felt believable, and I didn't feel as if the story bore any subtlety or richness below the surface.<br />The best I can figure this series is that it is not part of our time. Mordent's Need has many fans, though I've noticed that those fans are older readers that encountered the book a couple decades ago. It may be that the book is simply not meant to be read against today's standards and expectations, and I believe that fans who long for the days of yore and pulp fantasy will find a lot to enjoy about this series. However, it's clear to me that Mordent's need has not aged particularly well, and I wouldn't recommend it to those not specifically nostalgic for that generation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15411342670780990098" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


