  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3752797130" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3752797130" />
    <a title="Dan Nesbit" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85409260-dan-nesbit"><img alt="Dan Nesbit" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3752797130?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dan Nesbit" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dan Nesbit" href="/user/show/85409260-dan-nesbit">Dan Nesbit</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3752797130" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12338319820019305736">So much weird sex stuff. Where to begin?<br/><br/>This is the sequel to Mordant&apos;s Need... which also has lots of inappropriate bits (to say the least) and most of the same problems as this one. It is however oddly compelling, but man does it need some heavy-duty editing. <br/><br/>I went from page-turning, to what the fuck, to why the hell did that happen, to well that&apos;s out of character, to bored and back to page-turning again. That was pretty much the pattern of this book. The bit where they killed a pyromaniac c</span>
  <span id="freeText12338319820019305736" style="display:none">So much weird sex stuff. Where to begin?<br /><br />This is the sequel to Mordant's Need... which also has lots of inappropriate bits (to say the least) and most of the same problems as this one. It is however oddly compelling, but man does it need some heavy-duty editing. <br /><br />I went from page-turning, to what the fuck, to why the hell did that happen, to well that's out of character, to bored and back to page-turning again. That was pretty much the pattern of this book. The bit where they killed a pyromaniac cat by throwing shit at it was oddly one of the best parts. I think that says it all. Also, a green zombie child melts a chicken. It happens. <br /><br />But plot holes... ah the plot holes. The protagonists have so many chances to just kill the big bad and don't, so many ways to just neatly wrap up the story that get ignored. There's way too much running about for no reason, back and fort and a whole boat-load of nonsense decisions. <br /><br />The worst bit though has to be the weird sex stuff. Inappropes. It's just awful, and then the way it's glossed over after it happens is pretty wrong. Bad and wrong. I don't think if that happened to a character they would just bounce back for tea and biscuits the next morning. Sorry, Steve. I mean, it was written in the mid-80s, but still. Still. <br /><br />However, when alls said and done, Geraden and Terisa are two good characters, Artangel, the Tor, even Lebbick. They all worked well. Eremis was a stupid bad-guy, Gart was super dumb. Havelock, Elega and Kragen were quite interesting. The rest of them pretty much sucked and were a waste of paper.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12338319820019305736" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


